Today we recognize the start of Black History Month. To learn more about our local black history please visit The Sam Houston Memorial Museum's "12 Plus One" exhibit which will be on display from now until February 27, 2022. The exhibit reveals the ongoing research by the museum of the twelve individuals listed as property of Sam Houston in 1863 plus the one who was not listed. Each of the individuals highlighted in the exhibit were born into slavery and though their journeys were different, all eventually found themselves working and caring for the Houston family. They performed duties that were essential to the success of Sam Houston’s legacy until becoming freed citizens with emancipation. Exhibit is on display at the Katy & E. Don Walker, Sr. Education Center located at 1402 19th Street. Gallery hours are Tuesday - Saturday 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. and Sunday noon to 4:30 p.m.

What’s the happiest day at a bookstore? New release Tuesday! 😀 We’ve paired each book with a few similar titles to give you an idea of what’s inside 🦊 BOMB SHELTER by @marylauraphilpott : The author of “I Miss You When I Blink” returns in a gorgeously gut-wrenching memoir about our protective instincts - and the limits of the human body and mind. Read along as Philpott illuminates (often hilariously) what it means to throw a grenade at your own heart. TAKE MY HAND by @dolenperkinsvaldez : Montgomery, Alabama, 1973: New nurse Civil Townsend is determined to help the women in her community take control of their bodies. But when she’s tasked with providing birth control to two girls who have never even kissed a boy, Civil is forced to reckon with the real-world consequences of her care. THE WORLD ACCORDING TO COLOR by #jamesfox : A vivid exploration of seven elemental colors that reveals our unique and ever-shifting relationship with color. This is a vibrant celebration of how color reflects and shapes a culture’s hopes, fears, and prejudices. TRUE: THE FOUR SEASONS OF JACKIE ROBINSON by #kostyakennedy : a probing and richly researched account of one of baseball’s most significant figures. The book’s focus on four transformative years in the legend’s life - 1946, 1949, 1956, and 1972 - makes for a vividly unconventional biography. What is “Stop Asian Hate”? Content warning: contains mention of violence against Asian women A little over a year ago, a white man entered a massage parlor in the suburbs of Atlanta and open fired, killing 8 and wounding another. He cited a sexual addiction to Asian women as his motivation for his killing spree. His actions reflected centuries of imperialist, gendered violence towards Asian women. This tragedy sparked the “Stop Asian Hate” movement. This movement was meant to draw attention to the rise in anti-Asian, particularly anti-Chinese sentiment fueled by COVID-19 rhetoric and ongoing anti-Chinese messaging from American media. While this uptick in violence is more visible because of social media, xenophobic rhetoric degrading Asian communities in the US dates back centuries. “Stop Asian Hate” was trending on social media after the shooting and calls for anti-hate crime legislation began growing. However, these anti-hate crime bills were not written to protect the most vulnerable in Asian communities (those who are undocumented, don’t speak English, elders, refugees, etc), nor are these bills critical of the role of law enforcement in anti-Asian hate crimes. Our communities deserve better. Let us build a world where Black, Indigenous, and Communities of Color are safe and can thrive. To learn more about supporting Asian communities, particularly sex workers, in the face of growing anti-Asian sentiment, visit redcanarysong.net. #AAPIHeritageMonth

2 big storm systems on a collision course for about the Chamberlain area at about midnight. Then the two cells will jointly shove off to the East, impacting our area at around 3:00 AM. National Weather Service in Sioux Falls is not yet sure on what the system will look like after its convergence, or if it will pick UP steam, or dissipate afterwards. Whatever remnants survive should still pack a punch somewhat, and could regenerate as it moves over warm, humid grounds and lakes. Today we are highlighting an important moment from Black history that aligns with our focus area of financial stability: The Poor People's Campaign. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. believed that African Americans and other minorities would never enter full citizenship until they had economic security. Through nonviolent direct action, King and SCLC hoped to focus the nation’s attention on economic inequality and poverty. After building Resurrection City on the National Mall, they stayed in temporary shacks for over a month in a fight for jobs, unemployment insurance, and a higher minimum wage. #3000by2030 #yorkcountysc #liveunited #blackhistorymonth

Over the past few months, the US has been suffering from a shortage in baby formula, and families nationally have been greatly affected by this production crisis. In response, Congresswoman Jahana Hayes proposed the “Access to Baby Formula Act” which has been signed into law by President Biden on May 21, 2022. The act gives families easier access to baby formula through Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women, Infants, and Children (WIC) by lowering the requirements for eligibility during a time of crisis. In addition to this, Congresswoman Hayes and Senator Murphy traveled to a meeting with leaders of UConn Health and other members of the community to discuss further actions. Both the Congresswoman and the Senator are invested in avoiding another situation like this and want to insure that the consequences of this shortage are completely resolved. YWCA is deeply committed to insuring that everyone has access to health resources and is dedicated to assisting the under-served communities and how this situation has affected them specifically.

A man has been charged with a weekend shooting that killed an 18-year-old woman and seriously wounded a 19-year-old man in West Chatham on the South Side. #TimothyRoyster, 21, is accused of breaking into a home in the 800 block of East 83rd Street around 4:20 a.m. Sunday and shooting Ashlee Elliott, 18, and the 19-year-old man in the face, according to police and the Cook County medical examiner’s office said. They were taken to the University of Chicago Medical Center, where Elliott was pronounced dead, police said. The man was in serious condition, officials said. A 34-year-old woman in the home was not injured. Royster was arrested about 9:25 p.m. that night in the 7900 block of South Halsted Avenue, police said. He was charged with first-degree murder, attempted murder, home invasion and aggravated battery with a firearm, Chicago police said. Royster is due in bond court Tuesday. During #WomensHistoryMonth, we will be celebrating women's firsts in the Greater Boston community and beyond. In 2009, Ayanna Pressley won an At-Large seat of the Boston City Council, becoming the first woman of color to serve in the history of the Boston City Council. Ayanna occupied her seat for nine years until she won the seat for the 7th district of Massachusetts of the US House of Representatives, becoming the first Black woman to be elected from Massachusetts to the United States Congress. Ayanna's achievements and leadership make her a true pioneer for women not only in our community but across the nation.

Melt I idealized you from afar. Through a window, you looked absolutely magical. I looked at you with nostalgia covered eyes lost in wonder and excitement, eager to be playful and wildly enchanted. But the hype in my mind came nowhere close to your reality You were hard and cold, not soft and dreamy. You fell fast upon me, relentlessly covering me. Before I knew it, I was feet deep and struggling to get free. Frozen, with a frost bitten heart. You were snow... And I was unprepared for your cold storm. Now all I could do was wait for the seasons in my heart to change so your memory would melt and I could walk away. © Julia Pauhl, 2021

Quite disappointed in the Governors Veto today. This sends the wrong message to Kansas Girls who simply want to ensure fair competition. By Brad Cooper Gov. Laura Kelly on Thursday became the third governor to veto a bill banning or limiting transgender girls and women from participating in interscholastic sports for females. “This legislation sends a devastating message that Kansas is not welcoming to all children and their families, including those who are transgender – who are already at a higher risk of bullying, discrimination, and suicide,” Kelly said in a statement. As Kansans, we should be focused on how to include all students in extracurricular activities rather than how to exclude those who may be different than us. Kansas is an inclusive state and our laws should reflect our values. This law does not do that.” The veto had been widely anticipated since the governor had been signaling for days that she was opposed to the bill without outright saying she would veto the legislation. Kelly has always been a staunch advocate of the LGBTQ community. She took legal steps in 2019 to reverse a policy adopted under  former Gov. Sam Brownback’s administration to  allow transgender people to change their birth certificates consistent with their gender identity. The Legislature passed the Fairness in Women’s Sports Act short of having the two-thirds majority needed to override the governor’s veto. The House voted 76-43 for the bill with six lawmakers absent and not voting. It passed 26-11 in the Senate with three present and not voting. Senate President Ty Masterson told KCMO’s Pete Mundo last week that he thought he could get to the 27 votes needed to override the veto. He told Mundo that Kelly had no choice but to veto the bill. “Her party has gone so far that direction, they wouldn’t stand for it if she didn’t,” he said. But Masterson said he didn’t think the politics are in the governor’s favor. “She has a little trouble there because in general population that’s a 90% issue with us on fairness,” he said. Masterson promised a veto override. “There are a few (senators) on the margins,” he said. “We’ll see what they do when the pressure comes.”

Traveling while Black and queer can be challenging and often deters our community from seeing the world. Between the economic barriers to travel, discrimination, lack of education and resources, and unsafe conditions due to our identities, lots of us don’t feel comfortable exploring locations abroad. “Apogeo Collective is a boutique hospitality experience centering queer and trans people of color travelers. Their goal is to provide guests with rustic luxury, encourage exploration, and provide safe and open spaces where guests feel like they can lean into their most authentic & powerful selves to leave feeling inspired, energized, and rejuvenated.” In order for the space to be accessible, and to expand the offerings our community has to share, folks can apply to be Work Fellows for a discounted stay. Fellows are encouraged to bring whatever expertise they feel would be valuable to guests' experiences. In the past, fellows have cooked large community meals, built herbal apothecaries, facilitated cuddle workshops, and so much more. Apogeo Collective currently operates in San Juan del Sur, Nicaragua, in their flagship space. They are currently open for booking for their November/December 2022 and March/April 2023 community pop-up experiences. Email mailto:hello@ApogeoCollective.com for availability and more information. Very Asian Apparel • Available 02/22 2 PM PT at hemleva.com On January 1st, in a segment that discussed what Americans ate to celebrate the holiday, Michelle Li, a news anchor based in St. Louis shared what Korean Americans eat on New Year's Day. Dumpling Soup. The off the cuff comment by Michelle resulted in both support from those that felt included, but it also compelled a person to leave a derisive voicemail telling Michelle to "keep her Korean to herself" because she was being "inappropriate" & "very Asian". A flippant comment made by a viewer could have devastated Michelle, instead, the Asian community has used it as a unifying & uplifting cheer. A way for us to show that despite the rise in open xenophobia - that we are proud of all of the things that helped to create who we are today. Featuring my own hand drawn lettering, I am working with a local BIPOC Screen Printer to use water-based inks to have these incredibly soft shirts & sweatshirts made. I am proud of who I am. I am proud of my culture. I am proud to be an Asian American. I grew up eating Lunchables & Ramen for lunch, Sloppy Joe's over rice for dinner. My snacks included Dunkaroos & Pineapple Tarts. I love Egg Tarts (Dahn Taat) & Apple Fritters. Po Boys have a special place in my heart, right alongside Banh Mi's. I am a product of being a child in America that grew up loving Kit Kats & knowing that there were special flavors that you could only get at Asian grocery stores. I will show those that I love that I care about them through food, as my Asian family has always done, but I will tell you to your face that I care about you and your friendship, a product of growing up in America. I am an American, but I am also Very Asian, and very proud of it. Happy Lunar New Year 🥰🐯♥️ DONATION • A portion from every sale will be donated to @stopaapihate & @caasanfrancisco who "advocate for systemic change that protects immigrant rights, promotes language diversity, and remedies racial and social injustice." I will be donation matching up to 100% as well. There will be 2 Crops in Mustard & Black, 2 T-shirts in Water & Heathered Black, & 1 sweatshirt in Black. ♥️ #HEMLEVA #VeryAsian

Join us on Thursday, March 24th, for "Live Well, Sister!" with special guest Oludara Adeeyo, therapist and author of Self-Care for Black Women. . Based in Los Angeles, Oludara (Dara) works as a psychiatric social worker, where she assists individuals who are experiencing homelessness, substance issues, and severe/persistent mental illnesses. A Registered Associate Clinical Social Worker (ASW) for the state of California, she is passionate about helping people improve their overall well-being; especially, Black women. Before becoming a psychiatric social worker, Oludara spent seven-plus years working as a writer and editor. She has been an associate web editor at Cosmopolitan and the managing editor at XXL. . About Self-Care for Black Women: Between micro- and macro-aggressions at school, at work, and everywhere in between, it’s tough to prioritize physical and mental wellness as a Black woman, especially with a constant news cycle highlighting Black trauma. With Self-Care for Black Women, you’ll find more than 150 exercises that will help you radically choose to put yourself first. Whether you need a quick pick-me-up in the middle of the day, you’re working through feelings of burnout, or you need to process a microaggression, this book has everything you need to feel more at peace. . "Live Well, Sister!" is a weekly broadcast for Black women committed to living their best lives. An extension of Brown Girl Collective, special guests will include sisters who are experts in various areas: spirituality, self-care, relationships, life purpose/career development, financial savvy, community service, and the joy of living. Look for new episodes every Thursday.

#BMBFA Hidden Figure of the Week: Rebecca Lee Crumper • Rebecca Lee Crumper is the first Black woman to hold a medical degree in the United States. Though racial restrictions prevented Crumper from initially receiving formal training, she was accepted to the New England Female Medical College in 1860. Four years later, she earned her medical degree and in 1865, moved to Richmond, Virginia. With an earnest desire to study the diseases of women and children, Crumper went on to author the “Book of Medical Discourses,” one of the first medical publications by an African American. • #RebeccaLeeCrumper #HiddenFigures #BlackHistory #BlackHistoryMonth #BHM #BecauseOfThem #BecauseOfThemWeCan #BreakingBarriers

🎭 CJUI WISHES ALL OUR FRIENDS A VERY HAPPY PURIM!!! 🎭 חג פורים שמח The biblical holiday of Purim, instituted in the book of Esther, begins tonight, Wed. March 16. Every year, for almost 2,500 years since the time of Queen Esther, the Jewish people have celebrated the deliverance of the Jews of ancient Persia from intended annihilation. Since the ancient Persian Empire included most of the known world, including the land of Israel, this means that the Jewish population throughout the known world would have been destroyed. Because of this, the celebration of Purim is also significant for Christians! If the enemies of the Jews had been successful in annihilating the Jews of ancient Persia, there literally would have been no survivors who would become the ancestors of Jesus, born approximately 450 years after the time of Esther. In other words, if the Jews of Persia had been annihilated, there would have been no Jewish Jesus and therefore, no Christian faith rooted in the Jewish faith. This is one reason, among many, for Christians to appreciate the Jewish holiday of Purim and to stand with Jews everywhere in the ongoing battle against antisemitism and the delegitimization of the State of Israel.

Celebrating Asian American and Pacific Islander Heritage Month! Determined to break through the limits of her conservative upbringing, Jenny Phan began her involvement in the labor movement working at a unionized Catalyst dispensary. Although she loved her job, union, and coworkers, she realized there wasn't a lot of representation for people that looked like her. Wanting to further actualize the union message of strength and solidarity, Jenny stepped out of her comfort zone and advocated for her fellow coworkers by becoming the shop steward for her store. She eventually became a Special Project Union Representative for her union where she continues to play an instrumental role in setting the standard for the cannabis industry and cannabis workers. “This month I want to celebrate my AAPI family in the labor movement. Through my involvement in my union and the cannabis industry, I am reworking the narrative of what it means to be a working Asian person in America. I can be a strong outspoken Asian woman advocating for cannabis workers and workers overall while simultaneously being an example in the workplace with a relentless work ethic. To my AAPI family, I see you. Your labor matters regardless of what profession you’ve chosen. You are the community, and your voice is needed to achieve the working conditions necessary for all of us to thrive and succeed.”

In honor of Juneteenth, this year we are highlighting the work of our allies in California, who successfully passed the Racial Justice Act in 2020 and are now working to make it RETROACTIVE with the Racial Justice Act 4 All! Juneteenth is a reminder that freedom in America is imperfect because of racism. For the indigenous First Nations, for Black people, and for immigrants throughout this country’s history, the justice of liberty and emancipation was delayed and denied. But Juneteenth is also a reminder that hope endures for a future where we can all be free. Implementing the RJA law and passing the Racial Justice Act for All - AB 256 (Kalra) - moves us closer to that future. The RJA is changing the culture of the courts for the better. Racist discrimination is never harmless when it happens in the courtroom. The Racial Justice Act is shining a light on how widespread racism is in California courts. With AB 256 (Kalra) - the Racial Justice Act for All - the Legislature has the opportunity to apply the RJA’s protections equally to all people, not just those that went to court after 2020. This year, we must pass the #RJA4All to #ConfrontRacism not only in the future, but for Black & Brown people languishing in jails & prisons right now. It takes all of us working together to bend the arc of history towards liberty for everyone. California residents, please use this tool to contact your state senators to support #AB256 https://buff.ly/39xqLJY:=:https://secure.everyaction.com/Hiq5WDjGDUapgIcUW6NjXw2 !

Does your bio tells us what you do, Black Woman? Your Social Media Bio should be treated like your business store front. When somebody is visiting your page for the first time and they know nothing about your business, your bio can answer basic questions like who you are, what your brand is about and why they should care. You bio should always compel visitors to your profile to take action—whether that means clicking on your link, visiting your bricks-and-mortar shop, or simply following your account. What does your bio tells us? . . . #BuyFromABlackWoman #BlackWoman #BlackWomen #BusinessTips #Marketing #BusinessTips #SocailMediaHacks #Bio
